properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant rainfall, mild temperatures, and snow melt are expected over the next several days. Showers or periods of rain are expected over the next few days. While no significant amounts are forecast for today and tonight, rainfall is expected to intensify on Sunday into Sunday night and may require rainfall warnings. While it is too early to predict exact rainfall amounts, forecast guidance continues to suggest the potential for amounts possibly exceeding 50 mm in some areas over the next few days, with the highest amounts likely over higher elevations. The rain will combine with mild temperatures to cause significant snowmelt and an increased potential for localized flooding. The public is advised to follow subsequent forecasts and updates. Rainfall warnings might need to be issued later this weekend. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Storm Surge Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: We expect higher than normal water levels near the coast this morning. Warning of potential coastal flood conditions issued jointly by Fisheries and Oceans Canada (Science) and the Meteorological Service of Canada - Quebec Area, 2019-04-19. A low pressure system will generate strong northeasterly winds over the regions specified below. The combination of these winds and the fact that we are currently in a period of high tidal range and spring freshet could produce minor flooding along the coast near theses localities, at the dates and times specified (Eastern Daylight Time). Quebec City: 2019-04-20, 6 AM to 9 AM. ### Coastal flooding is possible along the shoreline. Coastal erosion is possible in vulnerable areas. Storm surge warnings are issued when water levels pose a threat to coastal regions. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.
